[1] Case update
- Thu 27 Sep 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=ec941c5bb1

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 26 Sep 2018:
- A total of 154 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, of which 123 were confirmed and 31 were probable.
- Of the 123 confirmed, 70 died and 43 are cured.
- 11 suspected cases are under investigation.
- 3 new confirmed cases in Beni.
- Of these new confirmed cases, 2 are known contacts from the same family who did not want to be vaccinated but who voluntarily went to the Ebola Treatment Center as soon as the 1st symptoms appeared.
- No new deaths.
- 2 new people healed in Beni.

News of the response
---------------------
Days of the dead city in Beni and Butembo
- This Thu 27 Sep 2018, the governor of the province of North Kivu, Julien Paluku, participated in the daily meeting of the coordination of the response to Beni and visited the CTE. He encouraged the teams and reminded them that they had all the support of the provincial government.

- In Butembo, the dead city day was lifted, and all commercial activities in the city resumed, allowing the response to resume field activities.

Collaboration of the community in Ndindi
-------------------
- All riposte activities were held normally in Beni this Thursday [27 Sep 2018]. In the Ndindi district, the cradle of resistance, the teams of the riposte were greeted without a hitch by the population. The local committee of community leaders had called for a catch-up session for non-immunized contacts and household decontamination of the latest confirmed cases from the neighborhood. Unlike the previous weeks, there was a lot of enthusiasm among neighborhood residents who voluntarily registered for vaccination.

Vaccination
-----------
- Launch of the vaccination of several contacts and contacts of confirmed cases of Tchomia that were located in Bunia. These contacts readily agreed to collaborate with the health authorities.
- Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 12 029 people have been vaccinated, including 4122 in Mabalako, 3662 in Beni, 1632 in Mandima, 884 in Butembo, 903 in Katwa, 270 in Masereka, 164 in Komanda, 156 in Tchomia, 121 in Oicha, 65 in Kinshasa (medical staff to be deployed), and 50 in Bunia.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[From this report, it appears control efforts are moving forward again. Even though even a few days without tracing contacts make a difference, the suspension of activities fortunately was brief. Nonetheless, a very high risk remains, and a highly coordinated effort is needed among all international organizations and the MoH in order to beat this outbreak in the midst of armed conflict. - Mod.LK]

- Wed 26 Sep 2018. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=56ab713782

A total of 151 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region: 120 confirmed and 31 probable.
- Of the 120 confirmed, 70 died and 41 are cured.
- 17 suspected cases are under investigation.
- No new cases confirmed.
- No new deaths.

News of the response
Days of the dead city in Beni and Butembo
-------------------
- The governor of North Kivu province, Julien Paluku, arrived in Beni on Wed 26 Sep 2018 to talk to civil society and the urban safety committee on 2 topics: insecurity and the epidemic of the disease.
- The field activities of the riposte in Beni resumed timidly this Wednesday [26 Sep 2018], and the teams were able to do their work with the community safely.
- A dead city day had also been declared in Butembo following the call of the pressure group "La Veranda Mutsanga" to sympathize with the people of Beni. As a result, field activities in Butembo also slowed down on Wednesday [26 Sep 2018].

Vaccination
-----------------
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 11 921 people have been vaccinated, including 4122 in Mabalako, 3652 in Beni, 1632 in Mandima, 884 in Butembo, 903 in Katwa, 270 in Masereka, 164 in Komanda, 121 in Oicha, 108 in Tchomia, and 65 in Kinshasa (medical staff to deploy).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

