[3] Protection of responders and civilians
- Wed 26 Sep 2018. WHO calls for protection of humanitarian workers and civilians in DRC
WHO [edited]
http://www.who.int/news-room/detail/26-09-2018-who-calls-for-protection-of-humanitarian-workers-and-civilians-in-democratic-republic-of-the-congo

The response to the outbreak of Ebola in North Kivu and Ituri provinces in the DRC is at a critical juncture, threatened by worsening insecurity, mistrust from affected communities, and extension into previously unaffected areas.

As of Tue 25 Sep 2018, the disease had affected 151 people and killed 101.

In recent weeks, a strong government-led response, supported by the World Health Organization (WHO), other UN partners, NGOs, and civil society, had resulted in a steady week-by-week reduction in cases.

But there is a risk now that hard-won gains may be lost.

1st, there has been an increase in frequency and severity of attacks by armed opposition groups. Attacks by armed opposition groups on the town Beni, in North Kivu, where the Ministry of Health and partners have based their response, have occurred with alarming frequency. Most recently a deadly attack on Sat 22 Sep 2018 left 21 dead, including 17 civilians.

As a result, WHO and its UN partners were asked to halt operations in Beni while the city mourns its dead. As of today [Wed 26 Sep 2018], some operations have begun to resume, but even a gap of 2 days has resulted in health workers not being able to reach contacts of Ebola patients to monitor their health or investigate alerts of potential cases.

Meanwhile, some families have chosen to care for sick relatives at home, often because they have been misinformed, and because a natural fear of the disease is now being exploited by local politicians.

Others sick with Ebola travel widely to seek alternative care, putting themselves, their families, and health workers at risk. This has brought infection to new locations, where teams cannot provide them with access to treatment or provide protective vaccines to their contacts. These include security red zones, which are difficult to access, and to areas bordering Uganda.

WHO calls on all relevant parties, and the governments or groups that have influence over these parties to help protect responders and civilians.

WHO also calls on governments in surrounding countries to accelerate the preparedness activities that they have begun, with WHO support, to ensure a level of readiness should they face cases of Ebola themselves.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

